The paper analyzes the content posted on Facebook during real world events, which falls under the category of social media analysis. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.SOC (Computational Social Science) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also uses stylometric features to classify spam content, which falls under the category of natural language processing, making cs.IR (Information Retrieval) and cs.CL (Computation and Language) likely sub-categories as well. Finally, the paper discusses the credibility and quality of information on social media during real world events, which falls under the category of cybersecurity, making cs.CYBER a possible sub-category.
